I mean, he is more important
than Abraham Lincoln, Martin

00:17:09.369 --> 00:17:11.260
Luther King, on and on and on.

00:17:11.260 --> 00:17:14.569
He is the man who began
the abolitionist movement.

00:17:14.569 --> 00:17:17.435
I guess 200 years from now
we're probably not going

00:17:17.435 --> 00:17:19.390
to remember a lot of
people, but we're really

00:17:19.390 --> 00:17:23.359
thrilled to be bringing him at
the forefront of the culture

00:17:23.359 --> 00:17:24.739
and into the Broadway community.

00:17:24.739 --> 00:17:26.280
ALAN SEALES: Well,
why do you think--

00:17:26.280 --> 00:17:27.279
why do we think that is?

00:17:27.279 --> 00:17:29.520
That, I mean, in America
we're taught specifically

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:31.390
the history of
America, which is just

00:17:31.390 --> 00:17:33.391
Abraham Lincoln pretty much.

00:17:33.391 --> 00:17:35.390
After I saw the show-- I
saw the show last week,

00:17:35.390 --> 00:17:36.885
and it was phenomenal.

00:17:36.885 --> 00:17:38.260
And I went home
and I immediately

00:17:38.260 --> 00:17:40.970
started researching
all about John Newton

00:17:40.970 --> 00:17:42.680
and about the British
side of all this.

00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:45.514
And was like, oh I thought
America did all this but like--

00:17:45.514 --> 00:17:47.430
CAROLYN ROSSI COPELAND:
Well, we were British.

00:17:47.430 --> 00:17:49.800
ALAN SEALES: Right,
we were British.

00:17:49.800 --> 00:17:53.710
Right, so how much did
you guys individually

00:17:53.710 --> 00:17:56.860
learn about this once you
started with the organization,

00:17:56.860 --> 00:17:58.520
with the show?

00:17:58.520 --> 00:18:00.760
